Html:
I came up with a little workaround for my problem. I am writing every single marker into an array at the same time it is placed on the map. If anyone is intrested:<br />
<pre><code>GMarkerGoogle marker = new GMarkerGoogle(Map.FromLocalToLatLng(e.X, e.Y), UnitMarker);      
//Placing the marker on mouse coordinates. UnitMarker is the custom marker.

UnitArray[UnitCounter, 0] = Convert.ToString(UnitCounter);
//Adding the uniqe UnitID to the array.

UnitArray[UnitCounter, 1] = Map.FromLocalToLatLng(e.X, e.Y).ToString();
//Adding the postion of the marker to the array.

UnitArray[UnitCounter, 2] = UnitMarker.Tag.ToString();
//Adding the tag to the array. The tag is set at the point where the bitmap (out of multiple bitmaps) is selected and has the same name as the selected bitmap.

UnitArray[UnitCounter, 3] = &quot;0&quot;;
//That is the orientation of the unit. 0 is pointing up. If I rotate the unit at a later point by 90Â° this number in the array will be increased.

UnitArray[UnitCounter, 4] = &quot;normal&quot;;
//Same as orientation, but if the unit is flipped or not.

marker.Tag = UnitCounter;
//Changing the Tag of the marker to it's uniqe ID. This is necessary to aling the array and the unit in further steps.

markersOverlay.Markers.Add(marker);
//Well, adding the marker to the overlay.

UnitCounter = UnitCounter + 1;
//Increasing the unit's ID.</code></pre>

For removing of a marker I use this code:<br />
<pre><code>void Map_OnMarkerClick(GMapMarker item, MouseEventArgs e)
{   
   if (e.Button == System.Windows.Forms.MouseButtons.Right &amp;&amp; Map.IsMouseOverMarker)
   {
       CMSMarker.Show(MousePosition.X, MousePosition.Y);      //Shows a Contex Menu Strip at the unit's location
       SelectedUnit = item;                                                       //Stores the item (item = selected marker)
   }
}

private void deleteMarkerToolStripMenuItem_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
   markersOverlay.Markers.Remove(SelectedUnit);                   // The item stored earlier is now removed
   UnitArray[Convert.ToInt16(SelectedUnit.Tag.ToString()), 1] = &quot;DELETED&quot;;
   UnitArray[Convert.ToInt16(SelectedUnit.Tag.ToString()), 2] = &quot;DELETED&quot;;
   UnitArray[Convert.ToInt16(SelectedUnit.Tag.ToString()), 3] = &quot;DELETED&quot;;
   UnitArray[Convert.ToInt16(SelectedUnit.Tag.ToString()), 4] = &quot;DELETED&quot;;
   UnitArray[Convert.ToInt16(SelectedUnit.Tag.ToString()), 5] = &quot;DELETED&quot;;
   //All the lines in the Array are marked as DELETED, expect the uniqe ID. The ID is still remaining in the array.
}</code></pre>

Maybe someone is intrested in that kind of stuff. <br />
I also could change the ToolTip of any given marker on the map. <br />
Rotating and flipping also works, however only for the last placed marker. If anyone has an idea how to flip any given marker on the map, please post.<br />
<br />
Thanks!<br />
